      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Managing buyer feedback during a Brisbane sale campaign: separating signal from noise
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Feedback is the single most direct read on how a campaign is performing, but most individual comments are noise. Here is how to weigh what you hear and decide when to adjust.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Two weeks into a campaign, the feedback is already pouring in. The agent's debrief after the first open home runs to twenty separate comments. The midweek inspection produced a written follow-up from one buyer and a phone-call summary from another. By the end of week two, the volume of opinions you have received about your home is overwhelming, and most of it sounds slightly contradictory.</p>

      <p>This is the point at which sellers commonly make the wrong move. They respond to individual comments by changing the styling, the price, or the campaign strategy. Or they retreat from the feedback altogether, treating it as personal criticism rather than market information. Both responses leave value on the table. The right approach is to treat feedback as a directional indicator, separate signal from noise systematically, and make changes only when the pattern is clear.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why feedback matters</h2>

      <p>Feedback from inspectors and the agent's read on buyer behaviour is the single most direct measurement of how the campaign is performing. The market tells you, in close to real time, what your property is worth, who is interested, and what is preventing serious buyers from moving forward. No other input during the campaign carries this much information.</p>

      <p>The challenge is that the volume is high and the quality varies enormously. Twenty comments per open home, multiplied across four to six weeks of campaign, creates hundreds of data points. Most of those data points are casual, anchored to the inspector's price range or property preferences rather than your actual buyer pool, and useful only when read against many similar comments. The work of managing feedback well is filtering volume into pattern.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What feedback you typically receive</h2>

      <p>The agent's verbal report on inspection numbers and quality. This is the highest-information input each week. How many people came through, what proportion were serious, who returned for a second inspection, who took the contract draft away to a solicitor.</p>

      <p>The agent's summary of buyer comments, both positive and negative. This is filtered: the agent has already removed the casual comments and grouped the patterns. A good agent's summary is more useful than the raw comments themselves.</p>

      <p>Any written follow-up from inspectors. This is rare and important when it happens. Buyers who write to the agent after an inspection are signalling more serious interest than those who simply walk through and leave. Even negative written follow-up ("we loved the home but the price is above what we have been pre-approved for") tells you something about the upper end of the buyer pool's affordability.</p>

      <p>Specific offers and their terms. This is the highest-quality data of the campaign. An offer at $1.45m with a four-week settlement and a small cooling-off variation tells you exactly what one specific buyer values your property at. Multiple offers in a similar range tell you what the broader market is willing to pay.</p>

      <p>Buyer comments about price, condition, location. This is the noisiest category and the one sellers tend to over-weight. A single inspector commenting that the kitchen is dated does not tell you whether the kitchen is genuinely a problem or whether that inspector simply prefers a different style. Patterns across many similar comments are what matters.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The signal in feedback</h2>

      <p>Consistent comments about price across many buyers are the most reliable signal that price needs adjustment. If five different inspectors over two open homes mention that the property is "stretched at this price" or "above what comparable homes have sold for," that pattern is real and is telling you the market's read of fair value. Individual buyers can be wrong about a single property's price, but five buyers cannot all be wrong in the same direction.</p>

      <p>Consistent comments about a specific feature (kitchen, bathroom, light, layout) are evidence that the marketing or presentation is missing the mark, or that the feature is genuinely a constraint on the buyer pool. If many buyers comment that the home feels dark, the photography may not be doing it justice, or the actual lighting may be a real issue that needs addressing through styling or staging adjustments.</p>

      <p>Specific feature observations from serious buyers (those who are following up with a second inspection or taking contracts away) carry more weight than passing comments from inspectors who are simply browsing. A buyer who has put in a written offer and is negotiating gives you precise information about what they value and what they discount; an inspector who walks through once and leaves a passing remark gives you almost nothing.</p>

      <p>Consistent comments about a specific competing property are also signal. "We are also looking at the home on Riding Road" tells you exactly which property your home is being benchmarked against. That benchmark is where your buyers are forming their value judgement, and it is information you can act on.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The noise in feedback</h2>

      <p>Comments from buyers below the property's price range are not actionable. If your home is on at $1.7m and an inspector is shopping in the $1.2m bracket, their comments tell you about a buyer pool that is not yours. The agent should be filtering these out of the summary, but if they are passing them through verbatim, you can discount them yourself.</p>

      <p>Passing concerns from inspectors who are not seriously engaged are noise. The inspector who walks through, makes a polite comment about "we'd want to update the bathroom," and never returns is not telling you that your bathroom is a problem. They are making conversation. Take them at face value: a passing comment from a passing visitor.</p>

      <p>Negative comments about features you cannot change (block size, aspect, location) may indicate the wrong buyer pool rather than a problem with the property. If buyers are commenting that the block is too small, your home is being inspected by buyers who want a larger block. The fix is not to apologise for the block; the fix is to confirm that the marketing is reaching the buyer pool whose preferences match your property.</p>

      <p>Comments designed to anchor a low offer are negotiating posture, not feedback. "The kitchen is dated, we'd need to spend $50k" from a buyer who is preparing to make an offer is a tactic. The buyer is signalling that they will discount the offer by the cost of the kitchen renovation. Treat it as negotiation rather than a market read on the kitchen's actual value.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The agent's filter</h2>

      <p>Experienced agents filter raw buyer comments into useful summaries. The summary should organise comments by category (price, condition, layout, location, marketing) and weight them by buyer seriousness. A good weekly debrief sounds like: "Six serious inspectors this week. Three commented on price being above market, two of those have moved on, one is still considering. Two commented on the kitchen, but neither was a serious buyer. The marketing seems to be reaching the right pool because the inspector quality is high."</p>

      <p>Ask the agent explicitly to distinguish "serious buyer feedback" from "casual inspector feedback." If the agent cannot make this distinction quickly, you are getting an unfiltered stream of noise rather than a useful read on the campaign.</p>

      <p>Request specific buyer follow-up. Have they returned for a second inspection? Have they contacted their solicitor about the contract? Have they ordered a building and pest inspection? Each of these steps takes a buyer further into commitment, and the agent should be tracking which buyers are progressing through the funnel rather than only reporting the volume of inspectors.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What "no feedback" usually means</h2>

      <p>Few inspectors and no engagement is itself a strong signal, even if no specific comment has been made. The most common reason for this pattern is that the price is too high relative to comparable listings, and buyers are filtering before inspecting. They look at the listing online, compare it to other homes in the same range, and decide that another home offers better value. They never inspect, so you never receive direct feedback, but the absence of activity is the feedback.</p>

      <p>This is the trap of waiting for "real" feedback during a slow campaign. The slow start is the feedback. Buyers are voting with their attendance, and the absence of attendance is the strongest possible signal that something needs to change. By contrast, a campaign with strong inspector volume and no offers is a different problem (typically presentation, marketing, or buyer-pool match), and the diagnostic is different.</p>

      <p>If two open homes pass with single-digit inspector counts and no written follow-up, the campaign needs a tactical adjustment. Wait one more week, and the cost in market presence and listing freshness compounds. The decision is rarely worth delaying.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Weekly feedback meetings with the agent</h2>

      <p>Set up a weekly review with your agent throughout the campaign. The aim is to look at the cumulative data, not the daily noise. The structure that works:</p>

      <p>Review the inspection numbers. How many came through this week, how does that compare to last week, how does it compare to similar campaigns the agent has run recently. Volume trends matter more than weekly snapshots.</p>

      <p>Review the comments by category. Group them: price (positive, negative, neutral), condition, layout, location, marketing. Look for the patterns rather than the individual comments. If three of seven serious inspectors commented on price, that is a pattern. If one of seven commented on the kitchen, that is noise.</p>

      <p>Agree any campaign adjustments. Are we adjusting the price guide? Updating photography? Refining the headline copy? Changing the open home schedule? The conversation should produce concrete actions for the coming week, not just a debrief of the previous week.</p>

      <p>Set objectives for the coming week. How many inspectors are we targeting at this weekend's open home? Are we expecting any specific buyers to return for a second inspection? Are there any contracts out that we are awaiting feedback on? Specific objectives create accountability and prevent the campaign drifting.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What NOT to do with feedback</h2>

      <p>Do not respond to every individual comment with cosmetic changes. The seller who hears one inspector say "the kitchen feels small" and immediately removes appliances from the bench, then hears the next inspector say "the kitchen feels stark" and immediately puts appliances back, is chasing noise. Cosmetic changes mid-campaign should be made only when the pattern is clear across many serious buyers.</p>

      <p>Do not let negative comments from below-budget buyers cause panic. Buyers below your price range will frequently rationalise their inability to afford the home by criticising it. Their feedback is the least useful feedback in the campaign and should be heavily discounted.</p>

      <p>Do not change the campaign strategy weekly. A campaign needs at least two weeks of execution before its effectiveness can be assessed. Constant changes to price, marketing, or open home cadence dilute the campaign's clarity in the market and signal weakness to serious buyers. Give changes time to work.</p>

      <p>Do not personalise the feedback. Comments about your home are commercial assessments, not personal criticism. The buyer who finds the layout unusual is not insulting you; they are making a judgement against their own preferences. Maintain emotional distance from the feedback so you can read it clearly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The price reduction trigger</h2>

      <p>If four or more weeks of campaigning produces low inquiry numbers, weak inspector engagement, and consistent price feedback from serious buyers, a meaningful price reduction is the right response. The campaign has already given you the market's verdict; further weeks at the same price typically produce diminishing returns, and the property starts to acquire the "stale listing" reputation that further suppresses interest.</p>

      <p>Small reductions ($5,000 to $10,000 on a property over $1m) often achieve nothing. The reduction is too small to register in buyer searches (which typically use round-number filters), too small to reset buyer expectations, and too small to draw new inspectors back to the listing. If a reduction is needed, structure it to be meaningful: large enough to drop into a new buyer search bracket, large enough to reset the anchor for buyers who had previously decided the property was overpriced.</p>

      <p>Time the reduction to maximise its visibility. A reduction announced alongside a refreshed photography set or a new headline gets more attention than a quiet price change in the listing. Combine the reset with a tactical refresh of the campaign's positioning.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>

      <p>Treat feedback as a directional indicator, not a precise instrument. The aim is to detect patterns across many comments, not to respond to individual ones. Five comments saying the same thing is signal. One comment saying something is almost always noise.</p>

      <p>Look for patterns from serious buyers across multiple inspections. Weight feedback by buyer seriousness: a buyer who returns for a second inspection or takes a contract away gives you better data than one who walks through once and leaves. The agent should be tracking which buyers are progressing through the funnel, not just reporting raw inspector counts.</p>

      <p>Give the campaign 2 to 3 weeks before making major changes. The first week is set-up and discovery; the second week is the first real read on the market's response; the third week is when patterns become reliable. Earlier changes are usually overreactions.</p>

      <p>Trust the agent's pattern-matching over your own emotional response, but verify the agent's read against the underlying inspection numbers. The agent has seen many campaigns and is generally a better filter than the seller, who sees one campaign with high emotional stakes. But the underlying data (inspector counts, second-inspection rates, contract requests) keeps the agent's interpretation honest. If the agent's read is "the campaign is going well" and the numbers say otherwise, the numbers are usually right.</p>

      <p>Above all, remember that feedback is information, not judgement. The market is telling you something specific about your property at a specific moment in time. The aim is to use that information to make the campaign work, not to take it personally or to over-react to any single piece of it.</p>

